Some information regarding methods and frequency of its use can be derived from ethnohistorical 
accounts near the time of the Conquest in Peru (Garcilso de la Vega, El Inca 1987 [1609]:511). 
While there are concerns about the nature and accuracy of their interpretations (Murra 1986), a 
common synthesis of their content suggests that royal efforts to restrict coca use began about A.D. 
1230 in the reign of Inca Roca, but the horticulture and use of the coca plant did not become a 
state monopoly until about two centuries later. At that time the plant acquired divine status and 
. played a central role in religious rituals. Under the strains of imperial expansion just prior to the 
Spanish Conquest, royalty found it necessary to share the privilege first with the nobility and then 
with progressively lower social classes until, at the time of the Conquest, all but the lowest classes 
enjoyed virtually unrestricted access to coca growth and use (Mortimer 1974:65; Phillips and Wynne 

1980:9). 
During the Postconquest period coca-leaf chewing became nearly universal among the oppressed 
native Andean peoples because of their perception of utilitarian benefits derived from chewing coca 
leaves, such as relief of fatigue and hunger, thus providing a lucrative market for Spanish hacienda 
operators. These perceived effects remain the principal stimuli for the persistence of coca chewing 
today (Carter et al. 1980; Hanna 1974), although in some areas coca chewing has become the symbol 
of Andean cultural identity (Allen 1988:220-227). In addition, it was also believed to be beneficial 
for a variety of physical ailments including gastrointestinal illnesses, dental caries, arthritis, head­
aches, sores, fractures, nosebleed, asthma, and impotence (Martin 1970). 
Such dramatically differing practices related to use of the coca-leaf plant during the past six to 
seven centuries suggest caution regarding the temptation to impose the Inca model upon previous 
populations among whom we have only archaeological evidence of its use. To gain more detailed 
information about the frequency and nature of coca-leaf-chewing practices by earlier people, a more 
discriminating measure must be employed. 

