Judging from archaeological evidence, coca leaf-chewing technique has probably changed little over the past 2,000 years. The dried leaves are chewed into a cheek "quid," and cocaine extraction or absorption is believed to be enhanced by addition of an alkaline substance (lime or plant ashes called yupta, l/iptum, or yuptak in Peru) (Lumbreras 1974:102; Plowman 1986; Schultes 1987). Absorption is both oral and gastrointestinal (Paly et al. 1980). Chewing of 20-60 grams of leaf daily is common in modern populations (Zapata Ortiz 1952) and provides a daily cocaine dose of 200­300 mg (Phillips and Wynne 1980: 14). Resulting plasma cocaine levels (up to mean values of about 250 nanograms [ng]/ml) (Paly et al. 1980) can approach the lower end of the range experienced by modern street users of some concentrated forms of cocaine. 
While the half-life of cocaine in the human body is measurable in minutes (Goodman and Gillman 1985:309), some of its metabolic products demonstrate considerable stability. This fact has been exploited recently by the development of both gas chromatography mass spectrometry (GCMS) and radioimmunoassay (RIA) methods (Baumgartner et al. 1982, 1989) to determine the presence of cocaine and benzoylecgonine (BZE), a cocaine metabolic product, in hair. Since BZE is absorbed by the cells of the hair follicle and subsequently incorporated into the shaft,.hair may accumulate evidence of the absorption and metabolism of cocaine within an individual's body over a period of several months. Scalp hair grows at a rate of 1-1.5 cm per month (Saitoh et al. 1967), and thus. 
' 
becomes virtually a timed record of exposure to cocaine. While this procedure was designed for forensic-science use on a living or recently deceased person, the stability of drugs in hair was demonstrated by a positive reaction when a hair sample of the laudanum-using Victorian poet John Keats was tested for that compound by RIA 167 years after his death (Bates 1963:635, 686; Baumgartner et al. 1989). 
In an effort to learn more about the details of Prehispanic coca-leaf use, and encouraged by positive reactions in our pilot study (Cartmell et al. 1991), we applied this procedure to samples of hair taken from the spontaneously mummified human remains of 163 individuals representing popu­lations from seven different cultures (Table 1) living on the coast and in the lower valleys of extreme northern Chile (near Arica at about latitude 18° south) over a period of 4,000 years. 
ANTHROPOLOGICAL FEATURES OF THE STUDIED GROUPS 
The Atacama Desert on the western slope of the Andes is the world's most arid desert. Stretching 
from about 17° to 27° south latitude, its interior is habitable below 3,300 m only within certain 
stream-containing valleys and along the coast. 
The Chinchorro culture represents the earliest (ca. 7000 B.C.) evidence of human occupation in 
the coastal area of northern Chile. Its members formed a tradition of preceramic fishermen and 
hunter-gatherers whose technological advances were associated with a simple maritime subsistence. 
Highland contact appears to have been minimal. Various origins have been proposed including a 
tropical one. 
The Quiani people probably represent the descendants of the Chinchorro. While they are still 
preceramic they developed a more complex fishing-tool technology and appear to have begun some 
agricultural experimentation and basketry. They represent a transitional group between their marine­
hunting predecessors and the subsequent agriculturists. 
About 1000 B.C. the Alto Ramirez people settled along the lower econiches. Believed to be 
immigrants from the Lake Titicaca area, they brought with them their highland traditions of camelid 
herding and agricultural practices. By A.D. 400 they were succeeded by the people of the Cabuza 
phase. These were agroganaderos (pastoralists and agriculturists) and represent Tiwanaku-related 
people. 
Just prior to the collapse of the Tiwanaku empire the Maitas Chiribaya became identifiable in 
the Azapa Valley near Arica in northern Chile. This group may be an adaptation to the local 
environments by the Cabuza people. Their ceramics acquire a richer palette, and the herding of 
camelids and their overall agricultural technology improved along with an increase in density and 
expansion of the population. 
Their successors, San Miguel phase peoples, represent a local development that created a rich 
style of handcraft, and increased exploitation of different econiches is apparent. The most recent of 

