MATERIALS AND METHODS 
Hair samples were obtained from the Human Biology Section files at the Archaeological Research Institute of the University of Tarapaca in Arica, Chile. These tissues were acquired by anatomic dissections of archaeologically excavated, spontaneously mummified human remains from coastal and valley sites in that region of the Atacama Desert. Age and sex were estimated using methods commonly employed by physical anthropologists (Ubelaker 1989:44-89). The populations studied are itemized in Table 1 and characterized above. Selection was made solely on the basis of availability of hair samples in the files. 
At least 30 mg of hair were removed from each individual studied. If scalp was attached the hair 
was transected as close as possible to the skin and orientation maintained within the plastic storage 
bag. After removal of gross debris the hair sample was rinsed once with 100 ml of sterile, distilled 
water. Following centrifugation the rinse water was saved for subsequent analysis to check for the 
presence of BZE. The hair sample was wrapped in a 4-x-4-inch sterile, loose gauze with stapled 
ends. This was placed in a plastic bag together with 100 ml of water containing .l ml of a commercial 
detergent shampoo (Prell, Procter & Gamble, Cincinnati, OH 45202); the hair was then thoroughly 
washed. After 10 more rinses the hair was air dried for 48 hours. The individual hair shafts were 
then cut into lengths of 1-3 mm. For the two individuals on whom we performed segmental analysis, 
a long braid was cut into 13-mm-long segments (about one month's growth), and each segment was 
prepared as an independent sample for analysis. 
The extraction procedure has been described by Valente (1981). The hair sample was suspended 
in a test tube containing 2 ml of .1 normal hydrochloric acid and extracted overnight in a water 
bath at 45°C. Then the hair was suspended in .1 ml of one normal sodium hydroxide and .9 ml of 
phosphate buffer at pH 7 .2 and centrifuged 10 minutes at 3,000 rpm. 
An aliquot of 25 ml of the extract was analyzed by radioimmunoassay according to the manu­
facturer's recommendation for determination of the cocaine metabolite in urine (Diagnostic Products 
Corporation 1990). Standard solutions of BZE provided in the kit include 0, 100, 300, 900, 2,700, 
and 5,400 ng of BZE/ml. In addition we also prepared 10 and 30 ng/ml standards. These were all 
analyzed at the same time as the hair-extract samples. An Abbott Auto Logic Gamma counter was 
used to obtain the raw counts per minute, and the data were entered into a Nuclear Medical Labs 
6000 CT computer that prepared a graph plot of standard concentrations against the percent of 
each standard found. This curve was employed to predict the concentrations of BZE in the individual 
hair samples. 
A hair sample for a negative control was taken from laboratory personnel, and for a positive 
control a hair sample was acquired from medical-examiner material from known cocaine users. A 
cutoff value of 5 ng/ml was employed to differentiate a "negative" and a "positive" result since this 
conservative value is commonly used in clinical studies. 
The first rinse water from 13 positive specimens with high values was analyzed to assess external 
contamination of the hair. A second aliquot was fortified with deuterated BZE and deuterated 
cocaine, extracted to isolate the BZE, and chemically derivatized. A control sample was also run to 
verify BZE levels. These samples were analyzed by a Finnigan GCMS in a select ion mode. Further 
instrumental and procedural details have been presented elsewhere (Springfield 1991). 
