Peruvian coast coca paraphernalia have been dated chronologically to the Late Preceramic period (2500-1800 B.C.), and Nazca and Moche human figurines (300 B.C.-A.D. 300) depicting coqueros (coca-leaf chewers) are common. At Tiwanaku sites as early as A.D. 400 (Plowman 1986; Schultes 1987) and in Arica in northern Chile, kits probably designed for hallucinogenic drug use, some including bags with coca leaves, lime, and drug-related utensils are common grave goods deposited with the funerary bundle beginning with the Cabuza phase (A.D. 400). A few such kits have even been found there associated with Late Chinchorro coastal burial sites, though the drugs employed by the Chinchorros have not been identified. Erices (1975) examined vegetals associated with the funerary bundles in three cemeteries near Arica, Chile: PLM-7, a coastal site occupied ca. 300 B.C.; AZ-6, a Tiwanakoid valley group from ca. A.D. 500; and PLM-4, a coastal site from the fifteenth century. No coca was found at the oldest site (PLM-7), but 5.7 percent of the Tiwanakoid tombs and 2.7 percent of the PLM-4 tombs contained coca in some form, including textile bags (chuspas) filled with coca leaves. The two later sites also contained seeds of Mucuma e/liptica, which grows only on the eastern Andean slopes, and this suggested evidence of active highland contact. Coca­leaf "quids" in mummified human remains from sites in the Arica, Chile, area are common after 
about A.D. 500. 
The BZE tests (Table 1) show no evidence of coca-leaf use by the Chinchorro group, a finding consistent with our expectations in a population with little archaeological evidence of ongoing trade with the highlands or northern coastal Peru. The coca plant grows best on the lower moisture-laden eastern Andean slopes. A coastal variant (Erythroxylon novogranatense var. truxillense) was known in northern Peru at least by 2000 B.C. (Plowman 1984), but there is, however, little reason to believe the Chinchorro people had any contact with northern Peruvians, since they left neither archaeological evidence of their presence north of Ilo, Peru, at about 17° south latitude nor non­indigenous, traded items. 
Although (with the exception of the Maitas Chiribaya population) the population samples of subsequent agricultural groups tested are small, the values indicate that at least some coca-leaf use can be traced to ca. 2,000 years ago (Alto Ramirez). In fact, the values for the Cabuza group reflect use by a significant fraction of the tested members. This is not surprising since the highland Tiwanaku cultures (the probable source group from which the Cabuza are derived) left an extensive archae­ological record of the more potent hallucinogenic drug apparati in their tombs and depicted in statuary (Berenguer 1985; Mulvaney de Penaloza 1984; Torres 1987). 
The frequency of coca-leaf chewing among the Inca-period group is of special interest. Funerary artifacts in their tombs provide no reason to believe this was a elite subgroup. Indeed, their worn, frequently patched and repaired clothing suggests they represent the lowest socioeconomic status. Nor do they fit the agricultural image of the Inca-period people and culture. Their beach-site location, abundant marine-oriented grave goods, and chemical dietary-reconstruction values (Aufderheide 1991) all clearly identify them as sea hunters (and, probably to a limited extent, sea traders). Radiocarbon dates also indicate the tested individuals lived during the last century of the Inca empire. The most probable model for this group would be to view them as a locally evolved population that came under political control of a local chiefdom, but that was permitted to continue functioning as a specialized subgroup of marine-resource harvesters, perhaps sharing (trading?) their products with highland dwellers. Admittedly more group members need to be tested to reach a desirable degree of validity, but finding even 9 positive results out of 13 individuals tested suggests that no significant restrictions for coca use applied to this group. It is emphasized, however, that these results cannot be used as a model for Inca practices at this period, because this small, remote group does not represent members of the Imperial Inca. 
The Maitas Chiribaya population is large enough to evaluate subgroup usage patterns. Table 3 
and Figure 2 suggest that frequencies were age dependent. The high frequencies apparent in the 
nursing age group (0-2 years) suggest maternal transfer of BZE both transplacentally (positive 
reactions in newborns) and via the breast milk as reflected in those up to at least two years old or 
more (Figure 2). Cocaine crosses the placenta, and in modern individuals has been found in neonatal 
hair (Baumgartner et al. 1982). Alternatively, medicinal cocaine administration (as tea?) to at least 
some of these ailing infants cannot be excluded, assuming they survived at least 10 days after such 
assumed treatment-the average interval between cocaine exposure and its appearance in the hair 

